# Synchronous FIFO Design & Verification (Verilog)



A parameterized synchronous FIFO designed in Verilog, verified using a self-checking testbench with a reference-model scoreboard, boundary condition testing, and fault injection — built and simulated in Xilinx Vivado (XSIM).



## Overview



A FIFO (First-In-First-Out) is a hardware queue — data written in comes out in the same order, commonly used as a buffer between two parts of a digital system running at different speeds or timing.



This project focuses equally on design and verification: rather than just building a FIFO and assuming it works, the goal was to build a testbench that automatically proves it works — and to prove that the testbench itself is trustworthy.



## Design Details



- Type: Synchronous FIFO (single clock domain)



- Depth: 8 entries (parameterized)



- Data width: 8 bits (parameterized)



- Flags: full, empty, almost_full, almost_empty



- Key design technique: Uses an extra MSB bit on the read/write pointers to correctly distinguish "completely full" from "completely empty" — both cases would otherwise look identical when pointers wrap around.



- Illegal operations (write while full, read while empty) are safely ignored rather than corrupting data.



## Verification Approach



- Self-checking scoreboard: A simple reference-model queue tracks expected values; every read from the DUT is automatically compared against it (no manual waveform inspection needed).



- Directed tests: Basic write/read sequence, verifying correct FIFO ordering.



- Boundary tests: Filling the FIFO completely (checking full asserts correctly), draining it completely (checking empty asserts correctly), and verifying illegal writes/reads are correctly rejected.



- Fault injection: Deliberately introduced a bug into the full flag logic (removed the pointer "lap bit" check) to confirm the testbench actually detects real failures, not just passing by default.



## Bug Story: Fault Injection Results



To validate that the testbench genuinely catches errors, the full flag logic was intentionally broken:



assign full = (wr_addr == rd_addr);



Result: This caused full to incorrectly assert immediately after reset (since wr_ptr == rd_ptr == 0), which silently blocked every write from the very first cycle. The testbench caught this immediately — not through a full flag mismatch, but through cascading data mismatches (every read returned 00 instead of expected values), since no data was ever actually stored.



PASS = 5 FAIL = 11



After reverting the fix:



PASS = 16 FAIL = 0



This confirmed the testbench reliably detects real design faults, including subtle ones where the symptom (data mismatch) appears in a different check than the root cause (flag logic).



## How to Run



1. Open Vivado, create a new project



2. Add sync_fifo.v as a Design Source



3. Add fifo_tb.v as a Simulation Source



4. Run Behavioral Simulation



5. View results in the Tcl Console (PASS/FAIL summary) and waveform viewer



## Results Summary



| Test Category | Result |



|---|---|



| Basic write/read order | Pass |



| Full flag boundary | Pass |



| Empty flag boundary | Pass |



| Illegal write (while full) | Pass |



| Illegal read (while empty) | Pass |



| Fault injection detection | Confirmed |



| Total | 16/16 PASS |



